article.description: Even with his team ahead by more than 20 in the second half, Gregg Popovich stomped along the sideline, screaming  at his players.
article.headline: Spurs beat Mavs for first time this year
article.linkText: Spurs, Parker hold off Mavs rally
article.story:
SAN ANTONIO (AP) -- Even with his team ahead by more than 20 in the second half, a scowling Gregg Popovich stomped along the sideline and screamed at his players. The coach of the San Antonio Spurs must have known what was coming. Dirk Nowitzki and Steve Nash slashed the Spurs' 26-point lead to five with nearly three minutes remaining before San Antonio righted itself and held on for a 113-100 victory over Dallas on Friday night. Nowitzki scored 17 of his team-high 21 points in the fourth, while Steve Nash -- who missed the previous two games with stomach flu -- collected seven of his 12 assists in the period. Afterward, a relieved Popovich summed up the night with, "All that matters is the win." Tony Parker scored 25 points and Hedo Turkoglu added 21 for the Spurs, who put together two big first-half runs to pile up a 59-33 lead at the break and 86-60 edge after three quarters. "We came out in the first half like it was unimportant," said Nash, who finished with 13 points. "It was like we were just punching the clock instead of trying to get somewhere." Nowitzki, held to 1-for-10 shooting through three quarters, went 7-for-9 in the fourth. His 17-footer with 2:56 left made the score 95-90. "When we were ahead we were playing aggressively," Parker said. "They came back on us because we stopped being as aggressive. We can't let that happen." Rasho Nesterovic hit Malik Rose with a pass for a layup for San Antonio, then blocked Antawn Jamison's reverse layup. Manu Ginobili was fouled on the same play and made both free throws to put San Antonio ahead 103-92. Dallas played the final 14 minutes without Michael Finley, who scored 13 of his 19 points in the third before he was ejected for throwing a forearm into Bruce Bowen with referee James Capers just a few feet away. Mavericks coach Don Nelson was tossed out seconds later for arguing the call on Finley. "We both bumped one another. He hit me and I hit him -- it was all in the heat of the battle," Bowen said. "I saw him coming, but I didn't know he was going to do anything in front of an official." Donn Nelson, who took over the Mavericks when his father was ejected, said he didn't see the Bowen-Finley dust-up, but he defended his player. "I don't think I've ever see (Finley) react like that in my five-plus years here," said Nelson. "There must have been a reason." Rose added 18 points and 10 rebounds for San Antonio, which played its fourth straight game without top scorer and rebounder Tim Duncan. Duncan suffered a left knee joint injury when these teams last met Feb. 26 in Dallas. The Spurs are 3-1 since Duncan got hurt. Nesterovic had his fourth straight double-double with 13 points and 15 rebounds. San Antonio averted its first-ever season sweep by the Mavericks, whose 33 first-half points were their lowest production of the season. Popovich was called for a technical foul at 8:06 of the first, and Steve Nash made the free throw to give the Mavericks their biggest lead of the game, 11-6. Parker made a 23-footer on San Antonio's next possession and then a 3-pointer to start a 23-7 run through the end of the quarter. Turkoglu scored on a dunk and a pair of 3-pointers during the burst, while San Antonio's high-energy defense limited Dallas to 3-for-13 shooting. The Spurs opened the second with a 17-4 run, capped by Parker's layup, to give them a 46-22 lead. Finley led a Mavericks charge in the third that cut the Spurs lead to 73-55 late in the period. He made five of his six shots, including his team's first 3-pointer, for 13 points before his run-in with Bowen.

Game notes
Finley has made 115 3-pointers in 56 games this season, four short of his career-high 119 set last season. ... The Mavericks are 9-5 this season against the other top teams in the West (Kings, Timberwolves, Spurs and Lakers), while the Spurs are 3-8.
